			<div class="sectionpartdiv"><div class="secheadtext"><!--<a href="/akbar-ka-durbar">-->How does one educate the poor and the needy to not vote for thieves and rogues? Is it a matter of "us" against "them" syndrome? Why are we not being represented by more honest and educated people? Do the needy become greedy as soon as they see power and money? Is there no such thing as unwavering morality?
<!--</a>--></div>
			<div class="bylinetext">Asked By - Krish Gopalan | October 30, 2012 </div>
			<div class="normaltaxt" style="font-size:14px;"><strong>M.J. Akbar answers:</strong> Don't worry about the poor. They know what to do in elections.</div></div>

			<div class="sectionpartdiv"><div class="secheadtext"><!--<a href="/akbar-ka-durbar">-->Is India on the track to becoming the most corrupt country in the world after Coalgate, 2G and CWG scams?
<!--</a>--></div>
			<div class="bylinetext">Asked By - Mukesh Rathi | October 30, 2012 </div>
			<div class="normaltaxt" style="font-size:14px;"><strong>M.J. Akbar answers:</strong> I am sure there are more corrupt countries in the world, but is that the kind of competition we should be aiming to win?</div></div>

			<div class="sectionpartdiv"><div class="secheadtext"><!--<a href="/akbar-ka-durbar">-->By promoting a corrupt politician like Salman Khurshid to Minister of External Affairs, isn't the UPA government compromising the integrity of India? He may do anything for money!
<!--</a>--></div>
			<div class="bylinetext">Asked By - Raghavan | October 30, 2012 </div>
			<div class="normaltaxt" style="font-size:14px;"><strong>M.J. Akbar answers:</strong> You certainly have a point.</div></div>

			<div class="sectionpartdiv"><div class="secheadtext"><!--<a href="/akbar-ka-durbar">-->Shouldn't the BJP take account of Nitin Gadkari's corporate funding or give up its crusade against black money?<!--</a>--></div>
			<div class="bylinetext">Asked By - Ramesh Sinha | October 29, 2012 </div>
			<div class="normaltaxt" style="font-size:14px;"><strong>M.J. Akbar answers:</strong> It should take account of public reaction.</div></div>

			<div class="sectionpartdiv"><div class="secheadtext"><!--<a href="/akbar-ka-durbar">-->What should India do to rid itself of the present-day kleptocracy that calls itself a democracy and to usher in real governance? Who is responsible for the present state of affairs ?<!--</a>--></div>
			<div class="bylinetext">Asked By - Hari S | October 29, 2012 </div>
			<div class="normaltaxt" style="font-size:14px;"><strong>M.J. Akbar answers:</strong> Democracy is suffering one of its periodic ebbs, but that is no reason to lose faith in it.</div></div>

			<div class="sectionpartdiv"><div class="secheadtext"><!--<a href="/akbar-ka-durbar">-->Many of our MPs are novices and inexperienced (including Rahul Gandhi). Can we bring about a law that one can become an MP only after they have served one or two terms as MLA?<!--</a>--></div>
			<div class="bylinetext">Asked By - Mayur Khokhani | October 29, 2012 </div>
			<div class="normaltaxt" style="font-size:14px;"><strong>M.J. Akbar answers:</strong> What a good idea - but then an MLA must be as responsible as an MP!</div></div>

			<div class="sectionpartdiv"><div class="secheadtext"><!--<a href="/akbar-ka-durbar">-->If it is accepted that communism is universally discredited, does it mean we should not attempt to remove economic inequality? If you agree that degrading poverty still remain a major problem, what would your advice be to people in power?<!--</a>--></div>
			<div class="bylinetext">Asked By - Unmesh Shukla | October 26, 2012 </div>
			<div class="normaltaxt" style="font-size:14px;"><strong>M.J. Akbar answers:</strong> Whether we are Communists, socialists or reformists, there is no question that the primary responsibility of any government has to be elimination of poverty.</div></div>

			<div class="sectionpartdiv"><div class="secheadtext"><!--<a href="/akbar-ka-durbar">-->The Congress and Left parties have connived to enable Muslim illegal migration from Bangladesh over years to build their votebanks and outnumber the indigenous populations in Assam and West Bengal. Do you agree that they are non-secular and biased against the majority community in India?<!--</a>--></div>
			<div class="bylinetext">Asked By - Karan Rao | October 26, 2012 </div>
			<div class="normaltaxt" style="font-size:14px;"><strong>M.J. Akbar answers:</strong> I can't quite understand the question.</div></div>

			<div class="sectionpartdiv"><div class="secheadtext"><!--<a href="/akbar-ka-durbar">-->Is it fair to have a mere 5,000 voters as sample to evaluate opinion of almost 40 million voters? I support Modi but the base is too thin to build a skyscraper.<!--</a>--></div>
			<div class="bylinetext">Asked By - Gulshan Vir Singh Sokhi | October 26, 2012 </div>
			<div class="normaltaxt" style="font-size:14px;"><strong>M.J. Akbar answers:</strong> Sample sizes are determined by scientific parameters that have been perfected over a long while.</div></div>

			<div class="sectionpartdiv"><div class="secheadtext"><!--<a href="/akbar-ka-durbar">-->What do you think is the gestation time for IAC/Anna movement to gain critical mass to change corrupt politics? Do you think IAC and Anna faction will merge in the future?<!--</a>--></div>
			<div class="bylinetext">Asked By - Chandan Kumar Koppula | October 25, 2012 </div>
			<div class="normaltaxt" style="font-size:14px;"><strong>M.J. Akbar answers:</strong> They have instigated a radical change in consciousness, but the next phase of action will be determined by the general elections, and the parties that win.</div></div>

			<div class="sectionpartdiv"><div class="secheadtext"><!--<a href="/akbar-ka-durbar">-->It appears Nitin Gadkari is in real trouble. What should the BJP do if it is a party with a difference?<!--</a>--></div>
			<div class="bylinetext">Asked By - Ravikumar Joyce | October 25, 2012 </div>
			<div class="normaltaxt" style="font-size:14px;"><strong>M.J. Akbar answers:</strong> You should read L.K. Advani's statement on this subject.</div></div>

			<div class="sectionpartdiv"><div class="secheadtext"><!--<a href="/akbar-ka-durbar">-->Gujarat Chief Minister Narendra Modi has not been proved guilty by any court but the liberal press and Congress brand him a killer. But when Congress leaders are caught in criminal acts their spokespersons say they should be treated innocent until proven guilty by courts. Why don't TV channels or press point this out?<!--</a>--></div>
			<div class="bylinetext">Asked By - Baburao Tipirneni | October 25, 2012 </div>
			<div class="normaltaxt" style="font-size:14px;"><strong>M.J. Akbar answers:</strong> You should ask those who use different standards.</div></div>

			<div class="sectionpartdiv"><div class="secheadtext"><!--<a href="/akbar-ka-durbar">-->Why are human values, the human touch disappearing? Are we slowly going back to barbarian days?
<!--</a>--></div>
			<div class="bylinetext">Asked By - Raghavan Vasudevan | October 23, 2012 </div>
			<div class="normaltaxt" style="font-size:14px;"><strong>M.J. Akbar answers:</strong> I have no idea why you should think so.</div></div>

			<div class="sectionpartdiv"><div class="secheadtext"><!--<a href="/akbar-ka-durbar">-->How far do you think Anna Hazare would go with his crusade against graft in India? Or is his much-hyped crusade going to be another flash in the pan?
<!--</a>--></div>
			<div class="bylinetext">Asked By - Syed Hasan | October 23, 2012 </div>
			<div class="normaltaxt" style="font-size:14px;"><strong>M.J. Akbar answers:</strong> Anna has already achieved as much as anyone could have hoped: he has incubated a change that will have far-reaching consequences.</div></div>

			<div class="sectionpartdiv"><div class="secheadtext"><!--<a href="/akbar-ka-durbar">-->Why do we spend money on bringing terrorists home and then subjecting them to trial (each trial, on an average, costs Rs 2 crore of the tax payer's money) when we could have asked the Saudis to behead him on some charge?
<!--</a>--></div>
			<div class="bylinetext">Asked By - Sandeep Badoni | October 23, 2012 </div>
			<div class="normaltaxt" style="font-size:14px;"><strong>M.J. Akbar answers:</strong> We in India live by a rule of law, and no price can be computed for the rights of a Constitutional democracy.</div></div>

			<div class="sectionpartdiv"><div class="secheadtext"><!--<a href="/akbar-ka-durbar">-->Is it in India's interest to engage with Pakistan, considering their helpfulness, or lack of it, in the Mumbai attacks investigation? Should we not opt for Israel-like tactics minus the bloodshed?
<!--</a>--></div>
			<div class="bylinetext">Asked By - Pratham Sharma | October 22, 2012 </div>
			<div class="normaltaxt" style="font-size:14px;"><strong>M.J. Akbar answers:</strong> What precisely are Israel-like tactics? Would you like the Indian Air Force to bomb Pakistan-held Kashmir on a regular basis?</div></div>

			<div class="sectionpartdiv"><div class="secheadtext"><!--<a href="/akbar-ka-durbar">-->If Kejriwal floats his party and contests elections, he is likely to eat into BJP's vote as well. What are the chances that, in such a situation, Congress will return to power? Is it possible that Kejriwal is being supported by Congress clandestinely?
<!--</a>--></div>
			<div class="bylinetext">Asked By - Ganesh Saraswat | October 22, 2012 </div>
			<div class="normaltaxt" style="font-size:14px;"><strong>M.J. Akbar answers:</strong> Intriguing thought, but the answer is a categorical no. Not even in politics do people cut their nose so devastatingly to spite their face.</div></div>

			<div class="sectionpartdiv"><div class="secheadtext"><!--<a href="/akbar-ka-durbar">-->Why would any educated Indian in his right mind join politics (although the country is in dire need of politicians who can lead the country towards progress)?<!--</a>--></div>
			<div class="bylinetext">Asked By - Sonali Sampat | October 22, 2012 </div>
			<div class="normaltaxt" style="font-size:14px;"><strong>M.J. Akbar answers:</strong> Because the educated Indian loves his country, and wants to do something about the mess into which it has been driven.</div></div>

			<div class="sectionpartdiv"><div class="secheadtext"><!--<a href="/akbar-ka-durbar">-->How did Marxism and religion co-exist in Kolkata during the Communist rule? How did the (middle class) intelligentsia of Kolkata accommodate both religion and Marxism and continue practising both for 35 years?
<!--</a>--></div>
			<div class="bylinetext">Asked By - Subhankar Basu | October 19, 2012 </div>
